1

00:00:04,700  -->  00:00:09,300
One way that you could think about clustered bar chart is that it's really a set of

2

00:00:09,300  -->  00:00:13,839
side-by-side univariate bar charts on different subsets of the data.

3

00:00:13,839  -->  00:00:17,594
This technique of creating multiple copies of the same type of

4

00:00:17,594  -->  00:00:21,899
plot but for different subsets of the data is called Faceting.

5

00:00:21,899  -->  00:00:24,574
We can use this for any type of plot,

6

00:00:24,574  -->  00:00:26,384
not just for bar charts.

7

00:00:26,385  -->  00:00:29,920
A violin plot for example could be thought of as very similar

8

00:00:29,920  -->  00:00:34,094
to a set of histograms faceted by a categorical variable.

9

00:00:34,094  -->  00:00:36,254
As a general technique,

10

00:00:36,255  -->  00:00:41,605
faceting is good for breaking down potentially complex patterns into simpler parts.

11

00:00:41,604  -->  00:00:46,894
This is especially useful if you have a categorical variable with a lot of levels.

12

00:00:46,895  -->  00:00:50,609
For example, this plot shows user registration dates

13

00:00:50,609  -->  00:00:54,700
faceted by month and arranged in a three by four grid,

14

00:00:54,700  -->  00:00:58,050
separating things out into multiple bar charts instead of

15

00:00:58,049  -->  00:01:01,049
a single long bar chart makes it easier to

16

00:01:01,049  -->  00:01:05,263
see the unusual number of January first registrations.

17

00:01:05,263  -->  00:01:08,640
One thing to be careful of when faceting is that

18

00:01:08,640  -->  00:01:12,950
your axis scales and limits are consistent across each subplot.

19

00:01:12,950  -->  00:01:17,150
A failure to have the same limits on each subplot we'll make it easier to have

20

00:01:17,150  -->  00:01:22,850
misconceptions about the overall frequency or value range for each subset of the data.

21

00:01:22,849  -->  00:01:25,954
Take for example these two plots.

22

00:01:25,954  -->  00:01:30,349
The plot on the left suggests that the two groups have approximately the same frequency

23

00:01:30,349  -->  00:01:34,750
and range but only if you don't pay attention to the axis ranges.

24

00:01:34,750  -->  00:01:39,989
The plot on the right fixes both subplots to the same axis ranges and clearly

25

00:01:39,989  -->  00:01:42,309
shows that there are more points of type B and

26

00:01:42,310  -->  00:01:45,760
that those points are generally of higher value than A
